    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-08-06T21:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-08-06T11:00:00-05:00" n="633"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d633">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">861.01/2237: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-document-content"
                            calendar="gregorian" notAfter="1941-08-06T22:00:00-04:00"
                            notBefore="1941-08-06T12:00:00-04:00">undated</date>.<lb/>[Received
                        August 6, 1941—10 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Following telegram has been received from Dickerson.<note n="93"
                        xml:id="d633fn93">Charles E. Dickerson, Jr., First Secretary of Embassy in
                        the Soviet Union. Ambassador Steinhardt had obtained permission from the
                        Soviet Government to send some Embassy personnel to Kazan, and this group
                        had left Moscow on July 18, 1941, in charge of Mr. Dickerson. See the
                        Ambassador’s telegram No. 1348, July 13, <ref target="#pg_898">p.
                        898</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <quote rend="blockquote">
                    <p>15. August 5, noon. Observation and personal contact indicate that the
                        following are among the organizations which have already been partly or
                        wholly transferred to Kazan from Moscow and Leningrad: R. S. F. S. R.<note
                            n="94" xml:id="d633fn94">Russian Socialist Federated Soviet
                            Republic.</note> Commissariats for Food Industry, of Trade Industry, of
                        Trade, and Local Industry, All-Union Commissariats for Food Industry, of
                        Trade, and Light Industry. In addition representatives of the All-Union
                        Commissariats for Rubber Industry, and General Machine build up Industry
                        have recently arrived. Part of the staff and equipment of Moscow <hi
                            rend="italic">Pravda</hi>, the Academy of Science, and the Committee for
                        Arts and for Higher Education, as well as a nucleus of the Central Club of
                        Red Army and Navy have also been evacuated to this city. A number of
                        Leningrad and Moscow plants producing food stuffs and synthetic and
                        reclaimed rubber have been moved here, and there are indications that
                        equipment from factories situated west of Kazan and producing machinery and
                        armaments is being installed in this district. Refugees from the Baltic
                        States, Leningrad and Moscow are continuing to arrive. Dickerson.</p>
                </quote>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
